              <span id="reviewTextContainer540968413" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12056331286644237507">I LOVED EVERYTHING ABOUT THIS BOOK!!! It is skillfully written with lovable characters and an engaging, dynamic plot. The historical details are richly detailed and accurate, yet do not overpower this beautiful love story. I didn’t realize it was the author’s first novel until I finished the book and immediately went to order something else by her. The Promise is an excellent debut and I am eagerly awaiting her next work!<br/><br/>The story is about Jane Grey, a baker who is raising a child as her own aft</span>
  <span id="freeText12056331286644237507" style="display:none">I LOVED EVERYTHING ABOUT THIS BOOK!!! It is skillfully written with lovable characters and an engaging, dynamic plot. The historical details are richly detailed and accurate, yet do not overpower this beautiful love story. I didn’t realize it was the author’s first novel until I finished the book and immediately went to order something else by her. The Promise is an excellent debut and I am eagerly awaiting her next work!<br /><br />The story is about Jane Grey, a baker who is raising a child as her own after the mother dies. After an outbreak of cholera, Jane decides to set up a trust so that five-year-old Pip would be cared for if anything were to happen to her. To raise funds, she decides to sell a necklace, the only thing of value that had been left to Pip by her mother. In the jewelry store Jane narrowly escapes arrest. Terrified and confused, she opens the paper the next day to discover the necklace belongs to a powerful duke and that she is the subject of a citywide manhunt.<br /><br />The Promise launches from there with a fast-paced plot filled with mystery and intrigue. We soon learn Jane is far more than the simple baker she appears to be. The hints about her past are dropped at a pace that made me want to keep reading to discover her secret. The relationship between her and Finn evolves from suspicion, to friendship, to budding attraction, and finally love. Finn has always been involved with beautiful, scandalous women, so he is confused by his interest in Jane. I enjoyed watching him evolve into a better, more substantial man through his love for Jane. I also liked that the relationship progressed believably and they didn’t jump into the sack right away, but when they did… whoa Nelly! It was hot! This book had a fairy tale ambience that appealed to me at the same time that it seemed realistic, like it could have really happened without straining the bounds of believability too badly.<br /><br />The characters were so well drawn and fleshed out that I felt as if I knew each and every one personally. From hard-working, kindhearted Jane who is hiding a secret past, to the rakish, handsome, Lord Finn and his grumpy, rough-edged friend Augustus, adorable, precocious little Pip, the acerbic Duke who is nursing a broken heart, to the meddling Dowager Duchess Justine, and even the butler Peckham—I loved every single one. The villain was a heartless bastard and I cheered when he finally got his just deserts. In fact, I became so emotionally invested in the outcome of the story that I had a hard time putting it down! The only bad part is that I didn’t want it to end! I can’t wait for Ms. Worth’s next book. Hopefully it will be about the Duke or Augustus. They deserve their own happily-ever-afters.<br /><br />Another thing I liked were the interesting historical details Ms. Worth included in The Promise. The information about the Sunday beer riots, the social unrest of the time instigated and agitated by activists like Karl Marx, the cholera outbreaks, and countless other bits of minutiae, transported me back to Victorian London. The way she described the neighborhoods, the docks, the jewelry store, all of it was so well done. I like it when history blends seamlessly into a story rather than making it feel like a textbook.<br /><br />Historical romances are my favorite genre. I read a lot and have a short list of favorite authors. Ms. Worth has been added to that list. She has a way with language that is rich and engaging and I will be on the lookout for her next title.<br /><br />Bravo!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12056331286644237507" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


